$t_max = random(2,4,0.5);
$ground = 2*$t_max;
$b = 16*$ground;
$max_h = $b*$t_max - 16*$t_max**2;

$funct = "\( h(t) = $b t - 16t^2 \)";

$h[1] = $b - 16;


$h_ran = random(10,50,10);
$D = $b**2 - 64*$h_ran;
$time_ran[0] = (-$b - $D**(1/2))/(-32);
$time_ran[1] = (-$b + $D**(1/2))/(-32);
$ans = "$time_ran[0] , $time_ran[1]";

BEGIN_TEXT
Question 30:
$BR $SPACE $BR
A ball is thrown into the air. Its height (in feet) \( t \) seconds later
is given by 
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
$funct
$BR
Based on the two equivalent forms used above to express the function $BITALIC h(t)${EITALIC}, answer the following questions:
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
a) What is the height of the ball 1 second after it has been thrown? \{ ans_rule(10) \} (include \{ htmlLink("javascript:unitspopup()","units") \} in your answer)
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
b) After how many seconds does the ball hit the ground? \{ ans_rule(10) \} (include \{ htmlLink("javascript:unitspopup()","units") \} in your answer)
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
c) At what time(s) is the ball $h_ran feet above the ground?  If there is more than one answer, give your answer as a comma separated list of values.  Do NOT include units in this answer.
$BR 
After \{ ans_rule(30) \} seconds (round to at least 3 decimal places)
$BR
$SPACE
$BR


END_TEXT

ANS( num_cmp($h[1], units=>"ft") );
ANS( num_cmp($ground, units=>"s"));
ANS( number_list_cmp($ans,tol=>0.01) );

$disp[0] = round($time_ran[0]*10000)/10000;
$disp[1] = round($time_ran[1]*10000)/10000;


SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
a) After 1 second, $BITALIC t $EITALIC = 1, and we wish to find the corresponding value of \( h(1) = $b(1) - 16(1)^2 = $h[1] \ \mbox{ft} \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) When the ball hits the ground, its height is $BITALIC h(t) $EITALIC =0.  We solve for $BITALIC t $EITALIC
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( h(t) = 0 = $b t - 16 t^2 \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( 0 = 16 t ( $ground - t ) \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
Therefore the ball is on the ground when $BITALIC t $EITALIC = 0 and $BITALIC t $EITALIC = $ground.  When $BITALIC t $EITALIC = 0 it is at its starting position, and when $BITALIC t $EITALIC = $ground is how long it takes for it to hit the ground again.  The ball hits the ground after $ground s.
$BR $SPACE $BR
c) When the ball is $h_ran feet high, its height is $BITALIC h(t) $EITALIC = $h_ran.  We solve for $BITALIC t $EITALIC
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( h(t) = $h_ran = $b t - 16 t^2 \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( -16 t^2 + $b t - $h_ran = 0 \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
We can use the quadratic formula to solve this equation for $BITALIC t $EITALIC with $BITALIC a $EITALIC = -16, $BITALIC b $EITALIC = $b, and $BITALIC c $EITALIC = -$h_ran 
$BR
\[ t = \frac{ -($b) \pm \sqrt{$b^2 - 4(-16)(-$h_ran)}}{2(-16)} \approx $disp[0] \ , \ $disp[1] \]
$BR
There are two solutions since it $h_ran feet high once at $BITALIC t $EITALIC = $disp[1] seconds (on its way up), and once again at $BITALIC t $EITALIC = $disp[0] (on its way back down).
$BR
END_SOLUTION
